  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "Article", "headline": "Is ETH a Scrabble Word? Yes — Valid in TWL & SOWPODS (6 Points)", "description": "ETH is valid in both TWL and SOWPODS. Worth 6 points, it's the Old English letter ð representing the voiced 'th' sound.", "datePublished": "2026-06-23", "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" }, "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" }, "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/is-eth-a-scrabble-word" } })} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [ { "@type": "Question", "name": "Is ETH a valid Scrabble word?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes! ETH is valid in BOTH TWL and SOWPODS. It's a strong 3-letter word worth 6 points that you can play confidently in any game." } }, { "@type": "Question", "name": "What does ETH mean?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "ETH (also spelled edh) is the name of the Old English letter ð. It represents the voiced 'th' sound as in 'the,' 'this,' or 'that.' Still used in modern Icelandic." } }, { "@type": "Question", "name": "What other letter-name words are valid in Scrabble?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Several letter-name words are valid: ASH (6pts), ESS (3pts), ZEE (12pts), ZED (13pts), PHI (8pts), CHI (8pts), PSI (5pts), ETA (3pts). These are valuable for scoring and versatility." } } ] })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Word Validity</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Is ETH a Scrabble Word? Yes — Valid in TWL & SOWPODS</h1>
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-23">June 23, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>5 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">ETH is a piece of English language history you can play on the Scrabble board. It's the name of the Old English letter ð — that crossed-d character representing the voiced "th" sound in words like "the" and "this." Valid in both TWL and SOWPODS at 6 points, ETH belongs to an elite group of letter-name words every serious player should know.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-green-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-green-950/30 to-emerald-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-green-500/70">✓ VALID</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">ETH</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-green-300 font-semibold mb-3">6 points · E(1) + T(1) + H(4) · Old English letter ð · Both dictionaries</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">ETH is valid in both TWL and SOWPODS. The name of the Old English letter ð (voiced "th" sound). High-scoring 3-letter word thanks to the H tile.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-green-400">6</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Points</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-green-400">✓</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid in TWL</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-green-400">✓</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid in SOWPODS</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-green-400">ð</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">The Letter</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">What Is ETH?</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">📖 Definition</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">ETH (also spelled <span class="text-white font-medium">edh</span>) is the name of the Old English letter <span class="text-white font-medium text-lg">ð</span> (uppercase Ð). It represented the <span class="text-white font-medium">voiced dental fricative</span> — the "th" sound in "the," "this," "that," and "bathe." Old English used both ð (eth) and þ (thorn) for "th" sounds. ETH remains in modern Icelandic and Faroese alphabets today.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Letter-Name Words Valid in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>ETH belongs to a family of words that name letters from various alphabets — gold for Scrabble players:</p>
